{"title_page": "Harold Stabler", "text_new": "'''Harold Stabler''' [[Royal Society of Arts|FRSA]] (10 June 1872 \u2013 11 April 1945) was a designer and craftsman in silver, enamels, pottery, glass and other materials. ''[[The Times]]'' described him as \"one of the most capable industrial artists of his generation, and a successful teacher\".<ref name=t>\"Obituary: Mr Harold Stabler\", ''The Times'', 14 April 1945, p. 7</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n{{multiple image|perrow = 1|total_width=300\n | align             = right\n | direction         = vertical\n | width             = 500\n | caption_align     = center \n | image1            = Ventilation panel, Manor House tube station - geograph.org.uk - 1401124.jpg\n | caption1          = Manor House\n | image2            = TURNPIKE LANE-02 240710 CPS (4837732348).jpg\n | caption2          = Turnpike Lane\n | image3            = Ventilation panel, Wood Green tube station - geograph.org.uk - 1401101.jpg\n | caption3          = Wood Green\n | footer_background = <!-- footer background as a 'hex triplet' web color (include the initial #) -->\n | header_align      = center\n | header            = Ventilation Grilles on [[Piccadilly line]]\n}}\nStabler was born in [[Levens]], [[Westmorland]], the son of George Stabler, a schoolmaster. He was educated at Heversham Grammar School, and was then apprenticed to a wood-carver in [[Kendal]] for seven years, after which he went to the art department of [[Liverpool University]].<ref name=rsa>\"Obituary\", ''Journal of the Royal Society of Arts'', 27 April 1945, pp. 284\u2013285</ref> He moved to London in his twenties, settling in the Hammersmith area associated with [[William Morris]] and his followers.<ref name=t/> From 1898 to 1900 he was manager of the [[Keswick School of Industrial Art]].{{sfn|Griffiths|2020|p=85}} From 1907 to 1937 he was head of the art department of the [[Sir John Cass Technical Institute|Sir John Cass Institute]], and from 1912 to 1926 he was also on the teaching staff of the [[Royal College of Art]].<ref name=t/>\n\nAs a craftsman, Stabler first made his name as an enameller. He exhibited at the [[Royal Academy]] in 1916, 1917 and later. His designs included a silver and enamel mace for [[Westminster Cathedral]], the ceremonial collar of the [[Royal Victorian Order]], and works for the [[Goldsmiths' Company]].<ref name=t/> He did not confine himself to hand-crafted works. According to an obituarist, \"In pottery, glass, and silver he designed for mass production by partly mechanical means with conspicuous success\". His work included designs for [[Pyrex]] glass. For [[London Transport (brand)|London Transport]] he designed posters and decorative work including a London-themed set of tiles used on the wall tiling of some new stations.<ref name=t/><ref name=\"eh_1401096\">{{NHLE | num=1401096 | desc=St John's Wood Underground Station - Details | accessdate= 6 May 2014}}</ref>{{efn|Stabler's set of tiles for London Transport comprised 18 designs: Underground roundel, [[Houses of Parliament]], [[The Crystal Palace|Crystal Palace]], [[St Paul's Cathedral]], [[55 Broadway]], [[River Thames]] (Swans over water), [[Thomas Lord]], and symbols taken from the Heraldic emblems of City of London ([[Coat of arms of the City of London|Dragon]]), County of London ([[Coat of arms of London County Council|Lion inside a cross above water]]) Surrey (Coronet and oak leaves), Middlesex ([[Flag of Middlesex|Crown over three heraldic seaxes]]), Bedfordshire (Eagle with castle, from the arms of [[Bedford]]), Hertfordshire ([[Flag of Hertfordshire|Reclining stag next to water]]), Kent ([[White Horse of Kent|Rampant horse]]), Sussex ([[Coat of arms of Sussex|Five martlets]]), Berkshire (Five maidens, from the arms of [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]]), Buckinghamshire ([[Flag of Buckinghamshire|Swan]]) and Essex ([[Flag of Essex|three heraldic seaxes]]).<ref name=\"eh_1401096\"/>{{sfn |Badsey-Ellis |2012 |pp=18-19}}}}  His obituarist in the ''Journal of the Royal Society of Arts'' regarded  Stabler as a considerable influence on London Transport's chief executive, [[Frank Pick]].<ref name=rsa/> Stabler was one of the founders of the [[Design and Industries Association]], and was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Arts]] in 1938.<ref name=rsa/> \n\nIn 1906 he married [[Phoebe Stabler|Phoebe McLeish]], a sculptor who collaborated with him in some of his decorative work.<ref name=t/> \n\nStabler died in Hammersmith on 11 April 1945, aged 72.<ref name=t/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n==References==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book | last=Badsey-Ellis |first=Antony |title= Underground Heritage | year=2012 |publisher=Capital Transport |pp=18-19 |isbn=978-185414-360-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last=Griffiths | first=Vivian |chapter=Canon Hardwicke Rawnsley| title=The Three Founders of the National Trust | year=2020 | location=London | publisher= Pitkin| isbn= 978-1-84165-898-8 |ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1945 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:British metalsmiths]]\n[[Category:British silversmiths]]\n[[Category:English silversmiths]]\n[[Category:People associated with transport in London]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{LTM photo|Harold Stabler}}\n*[https://www.ltmuseum.co.uk/collections/collections-online/posters?q=Stabler Harold Stabler posters] in the collection of London Transport Museum\n", "text_old": "'''Harold Stabler''' [[Royal Society of Arts|FRSA]] (10 June 1872 \u2013 11 April 1945) was a designer and craftsman in silver, enamels, pottery, glass and other materials. ''[[The Times]]'' described him as \"one of the most capable industrial artists of his generation, and a successful teacher\".<ref name=t>\"Obituary: Mr Harold Stabler\", ''The Times'', 14 April 1945, p. 7</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n{{multiple image|perrow = 1|total_width=300\n | align             = right\n | direction         = vertical\n | width             = 500\n | caption_align     = center \n | image1            = Ventilation panel, Manor House tube station - geograph.org.uk - 1401124.jpg\n | caption1          = Manor House\n | image2            = TURNPIKE LANE-02 240710 CPS (4837732348).jpg\n | caption2          = Turnpike Lane\n | image3            = Ventilation panel, Wood Green tube station - geograph.org.uk - 1401101.jpg\n | caption3          = Wood Green\n | footer_background = <!-- footer background as a 'hex triplet' web color (include the initial #) -->\n | header_align      = center\n | header            = Ventilation Grilles on [[Piccadilly line]]\n}}\nStabler was born in [[Levens]], [[Westmorland]], the son of George Stabler, a schoolmaster. He was educated at Heversham Grammar School, and was then apprenticed to a wood-carver in [[Kendal]] for seven years, after which he went to the art department of [[Liverpool University]].<ref name=rsa>\"Obituary\", ''Journal of the Royal Society of Arts'', 27 April 1945, pp. 284\u2013285</ref> He moved to London in his twenties, settling in the Hammersmith area associated with [[William Morris]] and his followers.<ref name=t/> From 1898 to 1900 he was manager of the [[Keswick School of Industrial Art]].{{sfn|Griffiths|2020|p=85}} From 1907 to 1937 he was head of the art department of the [[Sir John Cass Technical Institute|Sir John Cass Institute]], and from 1912 to 1926 he was also on the teaching staff of the [[Royal College of Art]].<ref name=t/>\n\nAs a craftsman, Stabler first made his name as an enameller. He exhibited at the [[Royal Academy]] in 1916, 1917 and later. His designs included a silver and enamel mace for [[Westminster Cathedral]], the ceremonial collar of the [[Royal Victorian Order]], and works for the [[Goldsmiths' Company]].<ref name=t/> He did not confine himself to hand-crafted works. According to an obituarist, \"In pottery, glass, and silver he designed for mass production by partly mechanical means with conspicuous success\". His work included designs for [[Pyrex]] glass. For [[London Transport (brand)|London Transport]] he designed posters and decorative work including a London-themed set of tiles used on the wall tiling of some new stations.<ref name=t/><ref name=\"eh_1401096\">{{NHLE | num=1401096 | desc=St John's Wood Underground Station - Details | accessdate= 6 May 2014}}</ref>{{efn|Stabler's set of tiles for London Transport comprised 18 designs: Underground roundel, [[Houses of Parliament]], [[Crystal Palace]], [[St Paul's Cathedral]], [[55 Broadway]], [[River Thames]] (Swans over water), [[Thomas Lord]], and symbols taken from the Heraldic emblems of City of London ([[Coat of arms of the City of London|Dragon]]), County of London ([[Coat of arms of London County Council|Lion inside a cross above water]]) Surrey (Coronet and oak leaves), Middlesex ([[Flag of Middlesex|Crown over three heraldic seaxes]]), Bedfordshire (Eagle with castle, from the arms of [[Bedford]]), Hertfordshire ([[Flag of Hertfordshire|Reclining stag next to water]]), Kent ([[White Horse of Kent|Rampant horse]]), Sussex ([[Coat of arms of Sussex|Five martlets]]), Berkshire (Five maidens, from the arms of [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]]), Buckinghamshire ([[Flag of Buckinghamshire|Swan]]) and Essex ([[Flag of Essex|three heraldic seaxes]]).<ref name=\"eh_1401096\"/>{{sfn |Badsey-Ellis |2012 |pp=18-19}}}}  His obituarist in the ''Journal of the Royal Society of Arts'' regarded  Stabler as a considerable influence on London Transport's chief executive, [[Frank Pick]].<ref name=rsa/> Stabler was one of the founders of the [[Design and Industries Association]], and was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Arts]] in 1938.<ref name=rsa/> \n\nIn 1906 he married [[Phoebe Stabler|Phoebe McLeish]], a sculptor who collaborated with him in some of his decorative work.<ref name=t/> \n\nStabler died in Hammersmith on 11 April 1945, aged 72.<ref name=t/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n==References==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{ref